# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: back-vowel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:back-vowel/affricate] An **affricate** is a consonant that begins as a stop and releases as a fricative, generally with the same place of articulation (most often coronal).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] It is often difficult to decide if a stop and fricative form a single phoneme or a consonant pair.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] English has two affricate phonemes, /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/, generally spelled *ch* and *j*, respectively.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] However, voiced affricates other than [d͡ʒ] are relatively uncommon.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] For several places of articulation they are not attested at all.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Much less common are labiodental affricates, such as [p͡f] in German, Kinyarwanda and Izi, or velar affricates, such as [k͡x] in Tswana (written *kg*) or in High Alemannic Swiss German dialects.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Worldwide, relatively few languages have affricates in these positions even though the corresponding stop consonants, [p] and [k], are common or virtually universal.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Also less common are alveolar affricates where the fricative release is lateral, such as the [t͡ɬ] sound found in Nahuatl and Navajo.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Some other Athabaskan languages, such as Dene Suline, have unaspirated, aspirated, and ejective series of affricates whose release may be dental, alveolar, postalveolar, or lateral: [t̪͡θ], [t̪͡θʰ], [t̪͡θʼ], [t͡s], [t͡sʰ], [t͡sʼ], [t͡ʃ], [t͡ʃʰ], [t͡ʃʼ], [t͡ɬ], [t͡ɬʰ], and [t͡ɬʼ].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Affricates are transcribed in the International Phonetic Alphabet by a combination of two letters, one for the stop element and the other for the fricative element.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In order to clarify that these form a single consonant, a tie bar may be used.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The tie bar appears most commonly above the two letters, but may be placed under them if it fits better there, or simply because it is more legible.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] This is derived from the IPA convention of indicating other releases with a superscript.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] However, this convention is more typically used for a fricated release that is too brief to be considered a true affricate.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Ligatures ⟨, , , /, ⟩ for the non-coronal affricates [pɸ] [bβ], [pf] [bv], [cç] [ɟʝ], [kx] [ɡɣ]/[gɣ], [qχ] [ɢʁ] have also been used.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Any of these notations can be used to distinguish an affricate from a sequence of plosive plus fricative, which is contrastive in languages such as Polish.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] However, in languages where there is no such distinction within a syllable, such as English or Turkish, a simple sequence of letters such as ⟨tʃ⟩ is commonly used, with no overt indication that they form an affricate.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In such cases the syllable boundary may be written to distinguish the plosive-fricative sequence in *petshop* /ˈpɛt.ʃɒp/ from the similar affricate in *ketchup* /ˈkɛtʃʌp/.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In other phonetic transcription systems, such as the Americanist system, affricates may be transcribed with single letters.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Single letters may also be used with phonemic transcription in IPA: [tʃ] and [dʒ] are sometimes transcribed with the symbols for the palatal stops, ⟨c⟩ and ⟨ɟ⟩, for example in the IPA *Handbook*.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The exact phonetic difference varies between languages.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In stop–fricative sequences, the stop has a release burst before the fricative starts; but in affricates, the fricative element *is* the release.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Phonologically, stop–fricative sequences may have a syllable boundary between the two segments, but not necessarily.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In English, /ts/ and /dz/ (*nuts*, *nods*) are considered phonemically stop–fricative sequences.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] They often contain a morpheme boundary (for example, *nuts* = *nut* + *s*).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The English affricate phonemes /t͡ʃ/ and /d͡ʒ/ do not contain morpheme boundaries.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The /t/ in 'worst shin' can be elided: [wɜː(ɹ)sʃɪn].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Stop–fricatives can be distinguished acoustically from affricates by the rise time of the frication noise, which is shorter for affricates.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] When affricates are geminated, it is the duration of the plosive closure that is lengthened, not that of the frication.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] For example, /t͜sː/ is pronounced [tːs], not *[tsː].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Polish has been reported to favour phonological gemination through rearticulation of the affricate, rather than the common method of lengthening the plosive closure.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In the case of coronals, the symbols ⟨t, d⟩ are normally used for the stop portion of the affricate regardless of place.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] For example, ⟨t͡ʂ⟩ is commonly seen for ⟨ʈ͡ʂ⟩, ⟨t͡ʃ⟩ for ⟨t̠͡ʃ⟩ and ⟨t͡θ⟩ for ⟨t̪͡θ⟩.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The exemplar languages are ones that have been reported to have these sounds, but in several cases, they may need confirmation.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The Northwest Caucasian languages Abkhaz and Ubykh both contrast sibilant affricates at four places of articulation: alveolar, postalveolar, alveolo-palatal and retroflex.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] They also distinguish voiceless, voiced, and ejective affricates at each of these.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] When a language has only one type of affricate, it is usually a sibilant; this is the case in e.g.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Arabic ([d̠ʒ]), most dialects of Spanish ([t̠ʃ]), and Thai ([tɕ]).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a dental stop with bilabial trilled release [t̪ʙ̥].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Although most affricates are homorganic, Navajo and Chiricahua Apache have a heterorganic alveolar-velar affricate [tx].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Itene, Oro Win, Sangtam, and Wari' have a voiceless dental bilabially trilled affricate [t̪ʙ̥] (see Trilled affricate).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Other heterorganic affricates are reported for Northern Sotho and other Bantu languages such as Phuthi, which has alveolar–labiodental affricates [tf] and [dv], and Sesotho, which has bilabial–palatoalveolar affricates [pʃ] and [bʒ].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] The coronal and dorsal places of articulation attested as ejectives as well: [tθʼ, tsʼ, tɬʼ, tʃʼ, tɕʼ, tʂʼ, c𝼆ʼ, kxʼ, k𝼄ʼ, qχʼ].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Several Khoisan languages such as Taa are reported to have voiced ejective affricates, but these are actually *pre*-voiced: [dtsʼ, dtʃʼ].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Affricates are also commonly aspirated: [ɱp̪fʰ, tθʰ, tsʰ, tɬʰ, tʃʰ, tɕʰ, tʂʰ], murmured: [ɱb̪vʱ, dðʱ, dzʱ, dɮʱ, dʒʱ, dʑʱ, dʐʱ], and prenasalized: [ⁿdz, ⁿtsʰ, ᶯɖʐ, ᶯʈʂʰ] (as in Hmong).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Labialized, palatalized, velarized, and pharyngealized affricates are also common.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Affricates may also have phonemic length, that is, affected by a chroneme, as in Italian and Karelian.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In phonology, affricates tend to behave similarly to stops, taking part in phonological patterns that fricatives do not.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Kehrein (2002) analyzes phonetic affricates as phonological stops.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] A sibilant or lateral (and presumably trilled) stop can be realized phonetically only as an affricate and so might be analyzed phonemically as a sibilant or lateral stop.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In that analysis, affricates other than sibilants and laterals are a phonetic mechanism for distinguishing stops at similar places of articulation (like more than one labial, coronal, or dorsal place).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] For example, Chipewyan has laminal dental [t̪͡θ] vs. apical alveolar [t]; other languages may contrast velar [k] with palatal [c͡ç] and uvular [q͡χ].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Affricates may also be a strategy to increase the phonetic contrast between aspirated or ejective and tenuis consonants.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] According to Kehrein (2002), no language contrasts a non-sibilant, non-lateral affricate with a stop at the same place of articulation and with the same phonation and airstream mechanism, such as /t̪/ and /t̪θ/ or /k/ and /kx/.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In feature-based phonology, affricates are distinguished from stops by the feature [+delayed release].
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Affrication (sometimes called *affricatization*) is a sound change by which a consonant, usually a stop or fricative, changes into an affricate.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] In rare instances, a fricative–stop contour may occur.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] This is the case in dialects of Scottish Gaelic that have velar frication [ˣ] where other dialects have pre-aspiration.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] For example, in the Harris dialect there is *seachd* [ʃaˣkʰ] 'seven' and *ochd* [ɔˣkʰ] 'eight' (or [ʃax͜kʰ], [ɔx͜kʰ]).
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Richard Wiese argues this is the case for word-initial fricative-plosive sequences in German, and coined the term **suffricate** for such contours.
[src:back-vowel/affricate] Awngi has 2 suffricates /s͡t/ and /ʃ͡t/ according to some analyses.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] The International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA) does not have separate symbols for the alveolar consonants.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] Rather, the same symbol is used for all coronal places of articulation that are not palatalized like English palato-alveolar *sh*, or retroflex.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] The bare letters [s, t, n, l], etc. cannot be assumed to specifically represent alveolars.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] The language may not make such distinctions, such that two or more coronal places of articulation are found allophonically, or the transcription may simply be too broad to distinguish dental from alveolar.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] If it is necessary to specify a consonant as alveolar, a diacritic from the Extended IPA may be used: [s͇, t͇, n͇, l͇], *etc.*, though that could also mean extra-retracted.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] The letters ⟨s, t, n, l⟩ are frequently called 'alveolar,' and the examples from the languages below are all alveolar sounds.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] Northwest Mekeo lacks coronal consonants entirely.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] A few languages on Bougainville Island and around Puget Sound, such as Makah, lack nasals and therefore [n] but have [t].
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] Colloquial Samoan, however, lacks both [t] and [n] but has a lateral alveolar approximant /l/.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-consonant] (Samoan words written with *t* and *n* are pronounced with [k] and [ŋ] in colloquial speech.) In Standard Hawaiian, [t] is an allophone of /k/, but /l/ and /n/ exist.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-affricate] An **alveolar ejective affricate** is a type of consonantal sound, used in some spoken languages.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-affricate] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is ⟨t͡sʼ⟩ or ⟨t͜sʼ⟩.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-fricative] An **alveolar ejective fricative** is a type of consonantal sound, used in some spoken languages.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-fricative] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is ⟨sʼ⟩.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-fricative] In many languages, it is allophonic with the affricate [ts'].
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-stop] In alphabets using the Latin script, an IPA-like apostrophe for ejective consonants is common.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-stop] In Hausa, the hooked letter ƙ is used for /kʼ/.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-stop] In Zulu and Xhosa, whose ejection is variable between speakers, plain consonant letters are used: *p t k ts tsh kr* for /pʼ tʼ kʼ tsʼ tʃʼ kxʼ/.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-stop] In some conventions for Haida and Hadza, double letters are used: *tt kk qq ttl tts* for /tʼ kʼ qʼ tɬʼ tsʼ/ (Haida) and *zz jj dl gg* for /tsʼ tʃʼ cʎ̥˔ʼ kxʼ/ (Hadza).
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-ejective-stop] In Oromo, one of the Ethopian languages that have this consonant, it is written with the letter x.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-affricate] An **alveolar lateral ejective affricate** is a type of consonantal sound, used in some spoken languages.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-affricate] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is ⟨t͡ɬʼ⟩ (or ⟨tɬʼ⟩).
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-affricate] Proto-Semitic *ṣ́ is believed to have been an alveolar lateral ejective affricate.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-fricative] An **alveolar lateral ejective fricative** is a type of consonantal sound, reported in the Northwest Caucasian languages and in Modern South Arabian languages.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-fricative] The symbol in the International Phonetic Alphabet that represents this sound is ⟨ɬʼ⟩.
[src:back-vowel/alveolar-lateral-ejective-fricative] [ɬʼ] occurs in the reconstructed Proto-Semitic language.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Back vowels are common across languages.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] In the PHOIBLE 2.0 convenience sample of phonological inventories, [u] and [o] are among the most frequently listed vowel segments, occurring in 88% and 60% of inventories in the sample, respectively.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Back vowels are often, but not always, rounded: cross-linguistically, non-low back vowels are commonly rounded (e.g. [u o]), while low vowels are often unrounded; front rounded vowels and back unrounded vowels also occur, but are less common.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] In strict IPA usage, the open front unrounded vowel is [a] and the open back unrounded vowel is [ɑ].
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] However, many phonological traditions use [a] (or the letter ⟨a⟩) more loosely for a low vowel, and recommend clarifying front vs. central/back values when the distinction is important.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] In descriptions of backness-based vowel harmony, a low vowel written /a/ may pattern with the back-vowel set even when its phonetic realization is not narrowly transcribed as [ɑ].
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Vowel backness is often treated as a distinctive feature (commonly [±back]) and can participate in processes such as vowel harmony, where vowels within a domain (often the word) systematically agree for backness and sometimes other properties.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] The vowel diagram used in IPA description is primarily a reference space for perceived vowel quality and does not directly encode vocal-tract shapes.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Acoustically, perceived vowel backness is correlated (roughly) with the second formant (F2), with back vowels tending to have lower F2 values than front vowels.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Lip rounding lowers vocal-tract resonances and can reinforce the acoustic profile associated with back vowels, which has been argued to support the common co-occurrence of backness and rounding.
[src:back-vowel/back-vowel] Vowels without dedicated IPA letters can be transcribed using diacritics for relative articulation (e.g. ⟨o̞⟩, ⟨u̠⟩, ⟨u̜⟩).
